title: For Sale:  NEW IN BOX:  Super Compact 9 mm
postcontent:
One of the most concealable pocket pistols ever in 9mm! There may be no slimmer, lighter, smaller or more ergonomic pocket pistol available today. The DB9 is easily one of the smallest 9mm semi-auto pistols you can get, and at 11 ounces one of the lightest.
NEW IN BOX – never fired.
Includes plastic case with original padding, owner’s manual, all paperwork, etc.
 
FEATURE LOADED:
Very clean lines and nothing to snag on. The only external controls are the trigger, magazine release, and takedown lever. The steel magazine latch is set at a very low profile to prevent accidentally depressing it and ejecting the magazine, something to consider in a pocket gun.
The magazine features a polymer finger extension base pad to help the shooter acquire a secure hold.
Slide: aggressively scalloped with forward and rear grasping grooves in a fish-scale type of pattern, for easy slide.
Frame provides as high a grip angle as possible and provides far greater control, reducing muzzle flip and perceived recoil. This design also provides more grip to hold onto in a very small package. Even with largish hands, you can place two full fingers on the front strap, and the back of the grip filled most of your palm.
The sights are easy to use and feature a low-profile, snag-free design. The white two-dot rear sight is dovetailed into the slide, and it is windage adjustable.
Striker-fired, locked breech, recoil operated.
Capacity: 6+1 round capacity.
Barrel and slide are made from billet 4140 through-hardened steel machined out of a solid block of chrome-moly.
Patent pending “Zero-Energy” striker firing system, which produces a clean and exceptionally smooth trigger squeeze with no stacking. The steel trigger with dual connecting bars has a 0.5-inch length of pull. The Zero-Energy striker system is one of the built-in safety features of the pistol and bears some explaining. It differs significantly from other striker systems in that the Diamondback does not preload the striker at all, allowing the trigger to do all the work. Other safety features include a firing pin block, which blocks the firing pin from going forward unless the trigger is fully depressed and helps prevents accidental discharges.
Finishes: The magazine catch, trigger and rails are all chrome-moly steel and black oxide coated. The trigger parts and the standard black-colored slide are Melonite coated for extra hardness, durability and corrosion resistance. This is a process that leaves a nitride finish directly on the metal that is much thicker and tougher than other finishes. The black color is applied on top of the Melonite finish.
Grip features a distinctive diamondback-pattern checkering on the sides, aggressive checkering on the front strap and a slightly extended palm swell on the back strap with its own distinct checkering pattern. Slight right and left thumb rests molded into the grip provide good memory pads for the hands. A beavertail at the top of the grip helps protect the web of the shooter’s hand from slide bite.
Diamondback pistols include a full lifetime warranty.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory TRP 1911
postcontent: I have a TRP I recently traded for.  If you look inside the gun, it looks as though it was never fired, but the previous owner said he fired a box of ammo through it.  So what I'm trying to say it, upon visual inspection, the gun looks like a brand new gun, inside and out.  I love 1911, but I already have a TRP that I want, which is the full rail Operator.  This one isn't one, but I just couldn't pass up on the deal.  Had this been a stainless steel, I would have kept it, but it is the Armory Kote.  I'm so itching to shoot this because I have how tight this gun is and how solid it is build.  It is the best money you can get for a semi-custom 1911.  Racking the slide takes a bit of strength because all TRPs come with custom-fitted slides.I am building my 1911 collection, but I'm more into the custom side.  My collection current has 2 Ed Browns, a full rail TRP Operator, and my EDC Kimber CDP Pro 2.  Right now, I'm trying to justify spending $4k on a Wilson Combat Protector, but not quite there yet.  I'm also into precision shooting, so I may be open to trading if you have something I'm looking for, and that could be ANYTHING.  For example, a TRP in stainless steel, heck, better yet a full rail TRP in stainless steel, a Beretta 96 Inox to a, maybe, Les Baer (not a big fan, but maybe love to own one), or even a nice gen 4 Lenovo X1 Thinkpad...yeah, weird I know...but I do prefer selling the TRP too.Looking to sell/trade within the city of Houston, preferably with a Texas resident since I don't know how it works with out of staters.  Please be of legal age and have a clean enough background that you can purchase a new one from a dealer.  I do have a LTC, so it'd be nice if you have one too, just to make it easy in the back of my mind.
